    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "While working on #780, I found that the output messages could be improved in some respects, e.g.:\r\n-  Format string parameters (file names, variable names, ...) are sometimes at the end of a message (\"Too many arguments for function: %s\"), sometimes inline (\"Argument of %s must be a List\").\r\n-  Format string parameters are sometimes put in quotes.\r\n- Some messages are split into multiple parts, e.g. [message for E325](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/src/nvim/memline.c#L3180). It's harder to translate such partial strings because some context is missing.\r\n- For error messages, words are sometimes capitalized after colons (\"E682: **I**nvalid ...\" vs \"E363: **p**attern ...\")\r\n- Minor wording differences, e.g. \"cscope\" is sometimes written \"Cscope\".\r\n- All-caps messages, e.g. \"(NFA) COULD NOT OPEN %s !\"\r\n\r\nFixing such issues should be pretty easy if there's an agreement on a \"message style\". The big downside, however, is that changes in the messages would probably require manually updating all existing translations afterwards (although the old translations might be recognized as \"fuzzy\" translations). If it is possible to create an `en.po` \"translation\", this could be circumvented while still improving at least some messages.\r\n",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Translations in any case will need to be updated: I have a huge number of new messages. The problem with Vim error messages is worse then that:\n- Some messages report no useful error locations (e.g. try `let d={'a': 1}|let i=\"abcdef\".(d.a(1))`).\n- All messages that show something show either start of the error or some identifier: no column and sometimes no way to automatically find it.\n- If you have any error in your expression vim will also show `E15` error with a copy of the expression which may be a useless noise.\n- Uncaught exceptions produce tons of errors.\n\nNow I have saner records of actual error positions, so I can produce more verbose errors: e.g.\n\n```\nError detected while processing test.vim:\nline 1, column 23:\n> let d={\"a\":1}|let i=d.a(1)\n|                       ^\nE15: Can only call a Funcref\n```\n\n. This will be incompatible in case somebody parses `:messages`/`:redir`, but since messages are localized (and thus not good candidates for parsing) and there is `v:exception` and `v:throwpoint` with `:try`/`:catch` it is probably not much of a problem.\n",
